        <body>

            <pb n="1"/>
            <p><addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>&#8212;reference&#8212;in
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cleveland&#44;</placeName> O. <date>Sept. 19th 5611</date></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My honorable &#40;Hochgeehrter&#41; friend&#44;</p>

            <p>I have received your letter of last month as well as fro<add>m</add><lb/>
                <placeName>Buffalo</placeName>. I am unable to make these cold<lb/> letters express
                my the pain I felt when I saw for<lb/> myself not privileged to speak to
                personally<lb/> and to have you in our midst for a few day<lb/> Not only I&#44; but
                also my friends whom I had<lb/> told of your intended visit to this city were<lb/>
                very happy. I hope that the wish which you<lb/> expressed&#44; namely to come here
                around this tim<add>e</add><lb/> next year will be realized&#44; if it pleases
                God.<lb/> I am writing an &#40;uncorrected&#41; copy now of<lb/> my work which I
                intend to publish and&#44;<lb/> with divine help&#44; I shall send you the
                    manu<add>s</add><lb/>cript within 3 weeks. My keenest desire however<lb/> is
                that you translate it as fast as possible<lb/> into English. For&#44; many people
                urgently<lb/> ask me to publish this work. Just now<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">again</hi> got the assurance of 50 subscribers</p>

            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>from <placeName>New Orleans</placeName>. Well&#44; I <sic>dont</sic> want to say<lb/>
                anymore. I am sure that your efforts will<lb/> rewarded also in a financial respect.
                After<lb/> the translation is <del>completion</del> completed I shall<lb/> take one for the
                necessary disbursements f<add>or</add><lb/> printing. When I send you the manuscript
                I<lb/> will give you detailed <del>report</del> instructions concerning the<lb/> binding. I am
                willing to have at least 2000<lb/> copies printed. enclosed you will find the<lb/>
                continuation of my biblical&#8211;exegetic lectures. Will<lb/> you be kind enough to
                precede it with the<lb/> following explanatory remarks. In<lb/> Occident &#35;102
                page 311&#44; the expression<lb/> &#8220;infinite extent&#8221; is&#44; as I see
                it&#44; no<lb/> contradiction in <add>&#63;</add> and also not <del>mere</del> just<lb/> an
                expression of sentiment but&#44; with <del>t</del> regards<lb/> to the universe&#44; as I used
                it&#44; a con&#40;per&#41;<lb/>ception of opinion. The universe does not<lb/> start
                anywhere and does not end anywhere<lb/> for no reason can be <del>stated</del> given that
                it<lb/> should start or finish anywhere. It is a<lb/> direct conception without
                which we cannot<lb/> think anything physical. Although we<lb/> presume parts in
                space&#44; space itself is<lb/> continual &#40;everlasting&#41;. A limited</p>

            <pb n="3"/>
            <p><sic>extention</sic> &#40;space&#41; is a geometrical or mathe<add>matic</add><lb/>al
                body. But the universe is an unlim<add>ited</add><lb/>
                <sic>extention</sic> &#40;space&#41; and that is the only
                significa<add>nce</add><lb/> we know of it. The universe is also no
                    produ<add>ct</add><lb/> of our mind &#40;intellect&#41; but a form of our<lb/>
                capacity to <del>perceive</del> imagine &#40;conceive&#41;. The<lb/> universe is not a
                conception and consequent<lb/> surrounded by a certain dark&#44; the imagination
                &#8220;space&#8221;&#44;<lb/> to which we must attribute this
                sig&#8211;<lb/>nificance&#44; too is <del>also</del> surrounded by <del>a</del> that certain<lb/> dark.
                <del>the talmud</del> In an excellent way the<lb/> talmud therefore terms &#8220;God&#8221;
                    <add>Hebrew</add> Hamakor<lb/>----because he alone fills the<lb/> infinite
                space&#44; which is nothing else but<lb/> a shorter expression for he who rides up
                on the cloud<lb/>
                <sic>furthermor</sic>&#44; page 112 ibid. in the 6th line from<lb/> top should read
                instead of &#58; where the heat of<lb/> the atmosphere ceases.....where the
                vapor<lb/> of the....render<lb/>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I The geographical rules to<lb/> which I refer<del>red&#44; are</del> I mean German<lb/> rules
                which are approximately 49 English<lb/></p>


            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>rules. I wish to call the attention of the<lb/> reader however that I wanted to
                indicate them<lb/> by the presumptive limits &#40;wrong German orthography<lb/> of
                the atmosphere&#44; that is the region of vapor<lb/> covering the earth&#44; for the
                boundary of <del><add>&#63;</add></del> warm<lb/> or&#59; &#40;which is same&#41; the beginning
                of the cold&#44;<lb/> that is the snowline starts already on the<lb/> equator where
                <del>it is most distant</del> <sic>the distant</sic><lb/> is greatest&#8212;15000 feet above
                the earth. I ask you<lb/> my friend&#44; to print this explanatory remarks&#44;<lb/>
                because I consider them essential <del>for</del> to a<lb/> better understanding of my last
                essay. Enclo<add>sed</add><lb/> you will also find a prayer which is prayed<lb/> in
                my congregation instead of the usual<lb/> but for this country inappropriate he who
                giveth victory<lb/> I attached the translation in German.<lb/> If it finds your
                approval you may translate<lb/> in English and recommend it&#8212;the Hebrew<lb/>
                text together with the English translation&#8212;<lb/> to the Jewish congregations
                of <placeName>America</placeName>.<lb/> The Lord of the Universe&#44; which <del>in co</del>
                may be<lb/> found in some prayer books&#44; does not find<lb/> the approval of the
                congregations and<lb/> is very seldom that it is recited in an</p>

            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>congregation. I will not utter any <add>&#63;</add><lb/> you&#44; yourself are able
                to judge it.<lb/> Conceiving the composition of my prayer<lb/> will have noticed at
                the very beginning&#44; <add>&#63;</add><lb/> I sanctioned&#44; biblically at
                least&#44; the freedom of<lb/> human beings&#44; or the natural human
                    <add>&#63;</add><lb/> by driving at Genes. 1&#44; 28. I think that in<lb/> this
                country&#44; my prayer suits the rabbinical<lb/> re rule
                &#40;regulation&#41;&#8212;&#8212;<lb/> &#8220;pray for the well being of the
                empire&#44;&#8221; better&#44;<lb/> than the Lord of the Universe<lb/></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you most cordially a<lb/> happy New Year and a Happy New Year<lb/> I remain
                your faithful friend<lb/>
                <persName role="author">Isidor Kalisch</persName><lb/> Rabbi </p>

        </body>
